  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the minimum income for Greece's Digital Nomad Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          €3,500/month net for a single applicant. Add 20% for a spouse (€4,200 total) and 15% for each child (€4,830 for spouse + one child). Income must come from foreign employers or clients—you cannot work for Greek companies.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why doesn't Greece accept travel insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Greece requires long-term residency health insurance covering medical and hospital care for your entire stay. Travel insurance is designed for short trips and emergencies, not comprehensive coverage. You need annual international health insurance or Greek private insurance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long can I stay in Greece with this visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The initial visa is 12 months. After arriving, you convert it to a 2-year residence permit. The permit is renewable indefinitely as long as you continue meeting income and insurance requirements. Total potential stay is unlimited with renewals.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I pay Greek taxes as a digital nomad?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          It depends on your stay duration. Under 183 days = not Greek tax resident, no Greek tax. Over 183 days = tax resident, but eligible for 50% tax reduction under the nomad regime. The effective rate with reduction is roughly 4.5-22% depending on income.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I live on a Greek island year-round?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, but consider practicalities. Larger islands (Crete, Rhodes, Corfu) have year-round services, healthcare, and reliable internet. Smaller islands may have limited winter services and variable connectivity. Research your specific island choice carefully.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long does the application process take?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Typically 1-3 months for the initial visa at the consulate. After arriving in Greece, the residence permit takes another 1-2 months. Plan for 3-5 months total from application to having your residence permit in hand.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

